1) What are parameters in a Java method, and why are they used?
-->👉 Parameters are variables defined in a method to receive values when the method is called.

    ✅ Why they are used:
    To pass data to methods
    To make methods flexible and reusable
    ✅ Example
    void add(int a, int b) { // parameters
        System.out.println(a + b);
    }


2) What is the difference between formal parameters and actual parameters in Java?
-->
| Type                  | Definition                              |
| --------------------- | --------------------------------------- |
| **Formal Parameters** | Variables defined in method declaration |
| **Actual Parameters** | Values passed during method call        |

void add(int a, int b) { // a, b → formal parameters
    System.out.println(a + b);
}

add(10, 20); // 10, 20 → actual parameters





3) Is Java pass-by-value or pass-by-reference? Explain with an example.
-->👉 Java is always pass-by-value

🔥 Important:
For primitive types → value is copied
For objects → reference is copied (but still pass-by-value)
✅ Example
class Test {
    int x = 10;

    void change(Test t) {
        t.x = 50;
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Test obj = new Test();
        obj.change(obj);

        System.out.println(obj.x); // 50
    }
}

👉 Explanation:

Copy of reference is passed
Both refer to same object → changes reflect


4) Can you pass an array or object as a parameter to a method in Java? Demonstrate with an example.
-->👉 Yes, both arrays and objects can be passed

✅ Example (Array)
void printArray(int arr[]) {
    for (int i : arr) {
        System.out.println(i);
    }
}

public static void main(String[] args) {
    int[] a = {1, 2, 3};
    printArray(a);
}
✅ Example (Object)
class Student {
    int id = 1;
}

void display(Student s) {
    System.out.println(s.id);
}






5) Can a method have multiple parameters? Explain with an example.
-->👉 Yes, a method can have multiple parameters

✅ Example
void display(String name, int age, double marks) {
    System.out.println(name + " " + age + " " + marks);
}

public static void main(String[] args) {
    display("Karthikeya", 22, 85.5);
}

